Meanwhile Julius Caesar’s assassins, the self-styled “ liberators,'’ had fled to the East, where in 42 B.c. they were defeated at the battle of Philippi by Antonius and Octavian. By a treaty made in 40 B.c. Lepidus was put in charge of Africa, Antonius of the East, and Octavian of the West of the Empire.

The chief Asiatic power threatening the Roman Empire was Parthia, and Antonius undertook against it a campaign, which was on the whole unsuccessful. Another danger to Rome in the East was the connection of Antonius with Cleopatra, queen of Egypt, for whom he had deserted his wife, the sister of Octavian.

Meanwhile Octavian had been strengthening his position in Rome. In 32 B.c. he found himself able to break with Antonius, and he defeated him at the naval battle of Actium in the following year.

It was now time for Octavian to bring to an end the period of civil strife, to establish law and order, and to restore so far as might be to Italy the qualities that the lawlessness of recent times had almost destroyed. Men of all parties, realising that the old republican government was a thing of the past, were ready to support Octavian, now styled Augustus, in his attempts at reform.

Some see in several passages of these and other Odes references to a conspiracy to kill Augustus, in which a leading part was taken by Murena, the brother of Mae enas’ wife Terentia.
